The first virtual operator will reach the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe
Perhaps the mobile phone market in the Czech Republic is quite mature and our operators offer virtually all services as their partners in Western Europe.
But there’s something missing – a virtual operator that obliges traditional ones to lower the price.
Maybe he won't be missing for a long time.
Of the fact that Czech operators belong to the most expensive in Europe, we have already written many times on Mobil.cz.
At the end of the day, he also confirmed it, which pointed out that the price of SMS is higher than in the rest of the Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of the regularization of roaming charges, perhaps a paradoxical situation will be created - for some customers of Czech mobile operators SMS will cost them less from abroad than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic are so high towards Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that would really like to start the fight.
Maybe it sounds absurd, even here we have three mobile networks and coverage highly above 100%.
On the other hand, the operators of the mobile telophons like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this sense, he also often emphasizes the head of the Czech Telecommunications Council, Pavel Dvo?k, who in the past has sometimes expressed that there is no place for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It is perhaps true that the traditional operator with their network no longer has many possibilities. (Although it would be difficult to find other frequencies by now.)
But there is still another possibility - the virtual operator.
Precisely the entry into the market of virtual operators has led to a considerable decrease in prices, to which the traditional operators should then react.
At the same time, even before the entry of sharks such as Tesko Mobile and Virgin Mobile into the market, similar voices as in us in Britain resounded in Britain.
However, it has been shown that the place for such operators is there and that they can be really successful.
After all, for example, we don’t have to go very far.
In February of this year we informed you of the arrival of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year this operator has managed to buy more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest local operator.
At the same time behind Mobilking is the Penta financial group to which in the Czech Republic it belongs, among other things, U:fon.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more concrete target group.
In order to work, it takes many fewer customers than to a traditional operator.
They do not carry with them, i.e., relatively high expenses for the creation, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
So in the world virtual operators usually come at a low cost, they offer low-priced calls and SMS, which is often in balance with the offer of the most restricted services
So for example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS that cost at least half of its competitors.
But as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can be a pretty good move even the bet on a group-target not least.
This operator is aiming specifically for men.
“True men choose the Mobilking operator they like and can be trusted,” says David Seibertz, CEO Mobile Entertainment Company, which produces this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether we can also say a similar concept like in Poland.
The press spokesman for Vodafone Miroslav epick doubts: “The Czech market is relatively small for a fragmented approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition, from the service point of view it is relatively saturated."
In the Czech Republic no possibility, say the operators of the mobile network
But it seems almost certain that if there will ever be an operator in the Czech Republic it will not be Mobilking.
“There is talk of the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic negotiations do not have many expectations.
The ignition of Mobilking will take place rather in the other countries of our area," Jana Studni?kov?, the press spokesman for the Penta financial group, said in a telephone dialogue for Mobile.cz
So he indirectly confirmed that the current operators in the Czech Republic are not very much in favour of this thought.
Rather, on the contrary, they try to do everything because no potential competitor is created.
For some time he has not hidden his interest in starting a virtual operator, the GTS Novera group that would like to take another step to become a real competitor of Telef?nika O2 in the field of corporate customers.
“We have a great interest in being able to offer our customers not only fixed services but also mobile telecommunications.
And the sooner you do it better.
We have negotiated repeatedly on this possibility with all the Czech mobile network operators.
We have already managed to progress in negotiations with some of them," said group spokesman Pavel Kaidl.
So maybe better times will come.
From the unofficial information it emerges that the first virtual operator will have to have it perhaps by the end of the year.
For now, however, around his creation stands an impenetrable wall of silence.
“Right now we don’t believe that in the Czech market there is space for the creation of a full-fledged virtual operator.
The Czech market, unlike other markets, is very specific.
Until now, no subject with a complex and serious project has turned to us,” he mentioned in his statement for Mobil.cz Vlastimil Sr?e of Telefònika O2’s press section.
The specificity of the Czech market is also the case with other operators.
T-Mobil press spokesman Martina Kemrov added in a rare agreement with the O2 statement: "For now we have not noticed any vital and beneficial commercial project for both of us, on which it is possible to continue to build."
He adds: “In the T-Mobil network a virtual operator will hardly appear by the end of the year.
At this time we must have already had to have a concrete agreement on the table, so that it could be considered on the horizon."
Vodafone focuses its attention rather than at achieving its 3G license requirements.
Miroslav adds: “We are open to the negotiations of potential virtual operators and this, especially in the context of spending and infrastructure sharing.
We consider this, from the point of view of customers, the most producing.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a common network for fast mobile internet.”
The competent authorities -with the complicit operators
The attitude of mobile operators can be easily understood, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would lead to lower prices and thereby to the decrease in profit.
Why then facilitate the rise of such a competitor?
The annoyances around the creation U:fon testify that when the operators keep to one thing they can row on the same side.
Perhaps the great pressure pressed against "T" in the period of creation of U:fon towards the company of T-Mobile.
This is a testament to public access information from the web pages of T.
But now U:fon serves as an argument for which not to accept the virtual operator.
Martina Kemrov said: “The environment of competition in the mobile phone market has been little enhanced by the entry of the fourth mobile operator into the market.
Regarding the type of mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that the entry of another competitor would place on him and especially on his high-end services.
Of the attitude of mobile operators, however, the complete disinterest on the part of the Czech regulatory bodies is surprising.
It is not just the attitude of the “T” that unfortunately in Czech Republic – unlike Britain and other developed countries – has no competence to interfere in economic competition.
That belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (OHS).
However, this has taken its typical position towards the whole problem.
"The entry of the virtual operator into the mobile telephony market would be possible after the conclusion of the contract for the rental of the necessary infrastructure between a mobile operator and a virtual operator had been implemented.
No such contract has been concluded so far because the offer of potential buyers probably wasn’t quite attractive for traditional operators,” said Kristi?n Chalupa, of the OHS External Relations section, in responding to our question.
Such a formulation statement by the representatives of the operators perhaps not surprising.
Instead, on the part of the office that must defend the interest of consumers and moreover take care of the fact that no one takes advantage of his position on the market, it is more than a delicate business.
Especially when Kristin Chalupa adds: “Abroad where virtual operators commonly work, we can observe that their entry into the market has contributed to lowering prices for mobile services.”
But of course the pressure on the proper functioning of the market environment and the lowering of prices do not belong to the interests of OHS.
Truly shocked in the whole situation is the almost exciting harmony of these three operators resulting from their reactions.
The question of whether it is really just a coincidence arises.
Equally as the exact price of gasoline for all petrol stations is certainly the result of coincidence and competitive struggle.
"The section found no signs of anti-competitive behavior regarding this fact and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
No operator has a dominant position, so it does not have a corresponding responsibility for its market behaviour.
The necessary tools for the opening of the mobile network market for virtual operators may also be lacking in the telecommunications regulator," Chalupa mentioned in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many controversial points.
Of course, there is the analysis of the relevant markets developed by T, according to which telecommunications are the only market from the point of view of economic competition.
On such a market, of course, no Czech operator has a dominant position.
But some legal experts offer another approach - for the creation of a virtual operator is always necessary the agreement of the operator of the network.
And the mobile operator has – at all logically – the monopoly of his network.
So for a certain portion it must be dominant by force.
But even if we don’t admit this argument, for OHS it should be a minimum alleviating that three mobile operators are going so strangely similar.
At the same time, complaints from the interested parties (including the aforementioned company GTS Novera) show that during negotiations with all operators they encounter very similar obstacles.
Unloading responsibility to T in telecommunications is a fairly frequent trick with which OHS keeps you out of the whole thing.
We have already seen this in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, it has not been possible to promote the expansion of the rights of ICT on the field of economic competition in telecommunications until the update of the recently approved telecommunications law, despite the fact that many experts have expected the improvement of the situation from this.
This fact the representatives of OHS must know more than well, but perhaps their interests are elsewhere.
You can do it when no one looks
While without us noticing, the functioning of these pseudo-virtual operators remains, of which there are even some in the Czech mobile networks.
These are companies that publish their price lists of mobile phone services, but they are only partially public.
These are usually multilevel marketing companies.
So for example, Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and a number of others offer their own mobile phone services.
The price lists of these companies usually reach only predetermined people.
The magic is that the company towards the operator is a classic business customer, who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer then receives offers of special prices (and more).
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit a similar presale.
"If the cases you are talking about, of which we will be interested, it could be a violation of the contractual conditions, and it could lead to the conclusion of cooperation with that company," Martina Kemrov? replied to the question in question.
But it is quite unlikely that such activity would not reach the ears of the subjects responsible for mobile operators.
Especially in the cases of the 3 companies mentioned, it can be thousands of customers.
No operator defends himself at the same time from such an attitude.
From the activity of these companies they derive a profit not indifferent and at the same time - unlike the real virtual operators - they are not damaged in any way with their official marketing.
Miroslav epick warns about possible problems: "The law allows similar speculations, but only a negligible percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
These must also accept that the SIM card in their phone is not registered in their name, so they cannot fully dispose of it as the regular customers of mobile operators.”
But this should be a strange minimum at the "T".
In addition, another issue opens up for OHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes to such an attitude, why do they block the creation of the virtual operator?
It is necessary to add that OHS has strong enough rights to unmask similar activities and if you do not want you will not have to settle for the explanation of the operators who have no idea of all this and that their commercial conditions prohibit it.
When we're not more expensive
As has already been said in the text several times, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile phone market has led to a significant lowering of prices for services.
At the same time, practically in all the countries where operators were born, traditional operators tried more or less to prevent their creation.
The arguments they used were virtually identical - market too small, to the too saturated limit, problems with the quality of services etc.
But in developed countries in these cases, the regulatory bodies have intervened in defense not of mobile operators but of their customers.
Both with formal measures and with non-formal pressure, then the creation of the first virtual operator was created and others joined.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory bodies launch the case from one to the other as a hot potato.
From our experience we cannot get rid of the feeling that the lack of clarity of skills in these cases makes him more than comfortable.
But let's not throw the towel.
If the background information is right and the virtual operator will really appear soon with us, the Czech mobile phone market will get back in motion.
