William Woodruff
Professor John Beckett writes:
Your obituary of William Woodruff (September 25) specifies that "in 1946 he resumed studying economic history at Oxford and in 1950 became a researcher in Houblon-Norman... studying at the same time for a bachelor's degree in science, one in literature and a PhD".
This follows from the note from the author of Woodruff in Beyond Nab End, but it is incorrect.
From 1946 to 1953 he was a university lecturer on economic history at the University of Nottingham, at which time he completed a PhD thesis on the British rubber industry, supervised by Professor J. D. D. Chambers, and later published in 1958 as The British Rubber Industry.
He spent 1950–51 in the U.S. as a researcher in Houblon-Norman, and the summer of 1952 at the University of Illinois, Harvard, and New York.
In 1953 he left Nottingham permanently for Illinois.
Because Woodruff chose to cover this part of his career, you don’t know.
Desecrated Muslim tombs while Austria turns right.
