"Photographer the master away from the scene to extract his character" G?nther Bauer, photographer
Neither heels nor ruffles nor dresses before.
Only the essence of the great masters of flamenco, stripped of the concentration that characterizes the interpretation, to look at the relaxed appearance of the man or woman.
On the one hand the artist.
On the other hand, the person.
Two inseparable faces, except in private, in those moments far from the audience, when the intimacy of a gesture, the depth of a stolen look or the expressiveness of the hands, are natural because they do not have to go on stage.
The German Gonther Bauer in "Flamenco-People" alternates the theatricality of some shots with singers, dancers and guitarists on stage with the less known side of these masters.
With this lens, the photographer offers an original iconography of flamenco, seizing it from different visual angles.
The exhibition, included in the programming of the Month of Flamenco Photography, reflects the international importance of this dance, every day ever greater," explains the artist and clarifies that in "Flamenco-People" they could also be ordinary people, but seeing the photos, the observer realizes that they are not the typical images of artists, performers or performers on the scene.
These people portrayed "on the street" are "artists able to convey passion, sadness, joy when they are on stage ... and to capture the audience.
To grasp the personality of these greats it is not necessary to portray them on stage,
because their personality and character are internal.
What interested me was creating an intimate atmosphere that would allow me to capture with the camera the personality of the great flamenco.”
With a passion for the festival "Cante de las Minas", Bauer began in 1997 a long journey aimed at portraying singers, guitarists or dancers using a plate camera.
They are portraits that, due to the type of machine and material, are reminiscent of classical photography.
The application of different stylistic techniques breaks with the traditional principles of the image, giving the photo modernity, according to an idea that reflects Bauer's own conception of flamenco: "A music with very traditional roots that evolves and is able to surprise every day."
Not the dancing, the singing or playing in itself, but the personality of the artist, his character, able to conquer the audience with his art.
The search for an encounter with the essential elements, with the magic that becomes visible in a certain way of feeling and being, are and have been the constant of this work, on display these days at the El Fotamata gallery.
Famous flamenco artists such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, among others, are in this selection of about seventy artists portrayed.
The project has become a sort of anthology of flamenco, and will soon be published in a book that will collect the portraits exhibited on the occasion of the exhibition.
The passion for portraits led Bauer to repeat the idea two years ago with "Portraits of Veterans" ("SportARTproject").
Although in "Flamenco-People" the concept is different, the photographer admits "I love to portray people, know them and be able to penetrate for a moment in their lives, let alone a long or short moment.
I think portrait is the most difficult genre in photography.
You meet or compare with people, characters that sometimes you don’t even know or who allow you just a few minutes to take the picture.
Beyond these circumstances, like a photographer, I always try to make my ideas come true.”
The collection of portraits of contemporary flamenco, entitled "Flamenco-people" is set up at the El Fotamata gallery, at number 20 of Via de la Mata, parallel to Via Alameda de Hercules, and will be open to the public until October 16th.
