The "ape car" to avoid collisions
As part of the development of accident prevention technologies, Nissan was inspired, this time, by nature, and in particular bees.
The Japanese company has created a robot that, taking as an example the flight of bees, knows how to avoid accidents.
It is the Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C, which is the first step towards collision prevention technologies.
Engineers at Nissan Motor Co.’s Advanced Technical Centre developed this small robot in collaboration with the Center for Scientific and Technological Research at the prestigious University of Tokyo in Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, Director General of Public Relations for Technology and Research and Brand Management, the BR23C is an expansion of Nissan’s four-area Safety Shield.
This robot is intended to improve the ability to prevent collisions in the manufacturer’s vehicles.
During the flight, each bee creates its own oval-shaped personal space that is very similar to the Nissan’s safety shield.
But the most important thing is the compound eyes of bees, able to see in all directions at an angle above 300 degrees, and that allow the insect to fly without interruption in its personal space.
To recreate this visual function, the engineers developed what they called a localization laser (Laser Range Finder).
This mechanism detects obstacles that are facing the BR23C for a radius within two meters and with a maximum amplitude of 180 degrees, calculates the distance from the object and sends a signal to an on-board microprocessor that immediately prevents collision.
“At a time when it detects an obstacle, the small robot mimics the movements of a bee and immediately changes direction by turning on the wheels at right or larger angles to avoid collision.
The most obvious difference with any assisted system is that the evasion maneuver is totally instinctive.
“If that were not the case, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles,” explains Toshiyuki Andoh, Director of the Mobility Laboratory and chief engineer of this project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot deviate upwards or downwards, nor even diagonally; it can only move in two dimensions and in the direction in which they can turn its wheels and not exploiting infinite directions and ways like bees do.
For this reason, the Nissan used a rotation function, in addition to acceleration and deceleration, so that the small robot can avoid collisions.
“This device only needs to process information every few seconds, and to act from this data.
It does not require the storage of information or the intuitive logic of the pre-trial maneuvers, so it can work without interruption and with only a couple of dozen KB of memory.
This may be surprising, but we’re not talking about gigabytes of memory, or even mega.”
It is the first step towards developing new technologies for the instant prevention of collisions, a technology that Nissan wants will be standard in cars within ten years.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries, which are lighter and more durable than the lithium-ion type.
Another potential future application of this technology could be the integration of the units with a GPS satellite navigation system to bring the driver to the destination avoiding the obstacles present in the route.
