Talking in the sleep
Some children speak at night.
I’m not referring to those who wake up very agitated to tell us something that happened to them the day before, but to those children who speak while remaining asleep.
The first time it happens, at most you take a fright, but in reality it doesn’t really matter.
It is a benign sleep alteration called somniloquy.
It occurs with a certain frequency, especially in children and adolescents.
Surely, most of you have told you that you had spoken in your sleep.
This phenomenon can occur in a very sporadic way (once in a lifetime, for example associated with an episode of high fever) or with a greater regularity (every day, once a week, once in the month ...), the day after the baby no longer remembers anything.
There is no single reason that can explain this phenomenon.
Sometimes they are episodes related to other sleep disturbances such as nightmares, nighttime fears, night enuresis (peeping in bed), or somnambulism, but it is not necessarily so.
As mentioned above may be associated with very high fever stages, stressful or overexcitation.
In any case, it is a phenomenon still little studied.
The intensity with which it appears is also extremely variable.
It can happen that the person speaks in a very quiet tone of voice, with loose words, almost in a whisper or that the opposite happens (scream, cries, long speeches ...).
In cases where the event is particularly intense, it would be appropriate to observe the child and possibly consult a specialist to check if there is any question that is generating an abnormal state of anxiety as an outlet to the situation.
We have said that this is a benign alteration so there is no treatment unless it is associated with other sleep disorders that can be treated (for example, if coupled with insomnia or stressful situation).
What can be done, however, is to consider a series of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child excessively before he goes to sleep.
Propose peaceful games and avoid programs or television series that arouse fear or suggest violence.
With very nervous children for whom it is tiring to relax, relaxation techniques can be used to help them acquire some inner calm.
This will allow the child to sleep more quietly.
Once the sleepers appear, try to keep calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will not remember anything that happened.
Useful advice
- Don't wake him up.
It is useless, because he is not aware of what is happening, and would interrupt his sleep.
Although he is talking, he is sleeping and therefore he is resting.
