The meeting - Blood is safe again
The Héma-Québec celebrated the tenth anniversary of its foundation yesterday, and its president, Dr. FrancineDécary, had every reason to rejoice, as the Hema-Québec has become one of the safest and most effective blood suppliers in the world.
And above all, it regained the public’s trust, seriously shaken by the scandal of infected blood in the years between 1980 and 1990.
As we know, the national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were infected with the acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C in the 1980s.
Faced with such a drama and the population protests, the Government of Canada conducted a public inquiry in February 1994, led by Judge Horace Krever, which aimed to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to spread recommendations to prevent the recurrence of such a disaster.
While Judge Krever was slow to draw up a report, some provinces set up a committee with the aim of devising a new blood management system in Canada.
In Québec, this mandate was implemented by the Gélineau Committee.
Following the Gélineau et Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Héma-Québec to supply Quebec and Société canadienne du sang (Canadian Blood Society) for all other provinces and territories.
In 1998, when Héma-Québec began its activities, just 38% of people said they still had confidence in the donation system in Quebec, recalls Dr. Décary.
The situation was mortifying.
Thanks to continued efforts to improve the safety of blood samples and field research over the next few years, we regained public confidence,” he explains before saying that at the beginning of 2008, about 94% of Québec’s population had confidence in the Heéma-Québec.
Dr. Décary is convinced that "trust is something extremely fragile".
Since its creation on 28 September 1998, the Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At the time, there were numerous cases in Europe of the human variant of the mad cow, a new manifestation of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, tells the story of her who has been chaired since 1998, the year of its foundation.
“And we didn’t know at all whether that disease could be transmitted through infected blood.
It was therefore based on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélinau reports, according to which when you have doubts and could achieve a serious disease, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease that manifests itself with a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, exclusion measures are taken.
In April 1999, the blood of those who had spent more than a month in the UK since 1980 was rejected.
Now, for a few years, it has been proven that without any doubt this disease is transmitted through infected blood.
This episode showed us that it made sense to apply the precautionary principle.”
In 1999 a much more efficient technique for the detection of HIV appeared on the market: nucleic acid (TAN) tests that allow to recognize directly in the blood of donors the presence of the virus and not that of antibodies against the same, on which the tests used until then were based.
The TANs have allowed to reduce the window period, that is, from the moment the person contracted the disease to the one in which the first viruses can be detected in the blood thanks to our techniques, explains the specialist.
It was possible to reduce that period to a duration of less than a week.
The risk of ignoring the presence of infected donors and not being able to identify them has thus significantly decreased.
These improvements have made it possible to considerably reduce the risk of getting AIDS with a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people run the risk of receiving infected blood from HIV.
“In other words, this means that you will need to distribute 12 million blood samples before someone gets infected with HIV.
Since the Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood samples each year, it will take more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmitted with a transfusion is found.
I believe that today we can feel calm in receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to recover health, says the head of the management of the Hema-Québec.
“Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
It is never known what pathogen will emerge in the system.
No later than a year ago, the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted in blood by an insect.
We must be constantly vigilant", continues Dr. Décary before pointing out that in addition to having safe resources, the Heéma-Québec must also provide enough.
“Necess increase as the population ages.
As the cures against cancer are more aggressive, patients often need a supply of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing population also has consequences for the number of donors, which on average makes up only 3% of Quebec-friendly inhabitants as donors."
However, all healthy people who are over 18 years of age and meet the eligibility criteria may, however, donate blood every 56 days, i.e. six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who offer themselves as donors are not accepted, because they are affected by AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have traveled to a country where the latter is widespread, they will be refused for a period of one year.
“With this 3%, we are able to maintain an inventory that can meet the needs of hospitals.
Cases of scarcity are very rare.
But we must renew the members of this group of donors as they age and can no longer make donations.
Now it is difficult to convince people to donate blood, but above all to hold them back and to incite them to become regular donors.
Nowadays life is so hectic that it is hardly an hour to donate blood,” says desolate Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, the Héma-Québec not only distributes blood samples, but also human tissues, including bone transplants, eye-globi heart valves and skin that is used almost exclusively for severe burns.
These tissues are analyzed, transformed and frozen before being deposited at the Héma-Québec which manages the only public bank of umbilical cord blood in Quebec.
In the umbilical cord, which was once considered a biomedical waste, abounds blood rich in stem cells that can serve to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"We celebrated, a few weeks ago, the inclusion in the bank of our thousandth sample of cord blood and we plan to take more than a thousand of them every year.
We should start proposing them for transplants early next year," says Dr. Décary, who describes this practice of cord blood sampling as very popular.
"Many mothers are disappointed not to have access to them", as the Héma-Québec does not have the necessary means to propose this complex and expensive program in all the hospitals of Quebec.
