Free opinion - The Orwellian Speech of Barrick Gold
In the September 17 edition, Le Devoir published a letter from M. by Patrick J. Garver, vice-president, director of Canadian mining company Barrick Gold.
Pursuing an Orwellian logic, the latter states that the world's largest gold company has filed a defamation lawsuit of six million against three authors and a small penniless publishing house with the intention of starting a "transparent public debate".
If it is true that the judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth they judge, especially in the case of a defamation lawsuit, but the law.
Without any surprise, this substantial difference is completely hidden by Garver.
Because for Barrick Gold, the best way to conduct a public debate would be to ruin anyone who dares to support a position contrary to his.
No matter the outcome of the trial, the writers and publisher of the Black Canada book will have to spend a substantial amount of money in order to organize their defense and fight, with decidedly unequal weapons, against an army of lawyers financed by the practically bottomless pockets of the mining company.
Moreover, in these effortless gunfights, the tactic is often to ruin the defendant in order to impose a consensual regulation that muzzles the opposition as well as frightening anyone or pronouncing themselves again on the issue.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it is in front of the public that she should have presented her view of the facts.
Contrary to what happens in many countries where Barrick Gold works, in Canada debates usually take place with the exchange of opinions and not with batons.
It would have been enough for the company to open its books, its documents, and establish a real debate, through newspapers, media, publications and the funding of teams of independent researchers who could shed light on the issue.
But Barrick Gold doesn’t seem to have too much confidence in public opinion and calmly rejects petitions and letters in support of the authors of Black Canada.
Perhaps Garver could explain how he can demand a “public” debate when his contempt for that same public is evident?
In the world of vice-president, it seems that this word only refers to the lawyers handsomely paid and not the set of Canadians; here is a rather narrow view of the concept.
In a democratic system, even denigrators have the right to speak.
What Barrack Gold doesn’t understand – or doesn’t want to understand – is that the public who supports the authors and publishers of Black Canada does it primarily because it rejects the brutal means adopted by the mining company.
This audience is ready to listen to Barrick and to judge, but on the basis of civil exchanges of opinion, and not in the perspective of what many perceive as a sort of gagging (seeing the "public debate", Barrick Gold has just given the authors of Canada Nero an ultimatum ordering them to suspend the use of that word...)
Beyond Garver’s surreal speech, the lawsuit filed by Barrack Gold constitutes a direct attack on the freedom of university research and the pursuit of truth, indispensable in every democratic society.
It denies en bloc the right to citation of authentic sources and to the debate on facts and interpretations, which are the basis of intellectual work itself.
If in a country like Canada it is impossible to study and discuss issues uncomfortable with the richest companies in the world, under pain multiple lawsuits, who can do it?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could do so by following scientific norms as the authors of Canada Nero do.
He has a right to reply.
For a long time, the university environment, of which we are part, is able to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold's excessive measures clearly show that, contrary to its claims, it does not seek a transparent debate at all.
This is at the expense of the university world, as is the same public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to take measures that can limit unfair lawsuits.
