The psychology of excess liking: Why spend more money?
At auctions, buyers are inclined to spend more, to overestimate the goods.
Neurologists and economists, researchers at the University of New York have managed to uncover the neuro-economic underpinnings of this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to their study in the journal Science, men don’t want to be left behind in a race such as the eBay auction, so they’re willing to pay a higher price.
The research sought to trace the nervous pattern of this "game" at the level of the nervous system through experimental rods.
One group of volunteers played the lotto, the other group of players participated in an auction while with the functional magnetic resonance imaging method (fMRI) they examined the active areas of the brains of the participants in the experiment.
In both games the participants could win money, but in the game of the rod, in which the substantial element is to licit more than the other, the striped body under the cerebral cortex enters intensively function when it is lost in the game.
This brain area, in addition to other functions, plays a role in the "self-gratification" mechanism of the nervous system.
Therefore, according to the researchers, the rise in the price is explained by the vehement reaction of the striatum body.
To support their theory, the research group’s economists carried out a financial pursuit survey.
In this survey, three groups set up against a partner under different conditions.
They reported to the control group how much was the real value of the product in question and they made their bet.
To another group, in addition to this, they promised that in the case of winning they will receive another prize of 15 dollars.
