Hepatitis: When to go to the doctor?
Nearly half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, but chronic liver disease is mentioned in Hungary among the leading causes of death.
In Hungary the number of hepatitis patients amounts to one hundred thousand, of which only 7,000 are treated: the reason is that many patients do not know they are infected.
The definition of hepatitis is the collective name of contagious liver diseases caused by several viruses.
There are many similarities between symptoms, typical of hepatitis and jaundice, but their pathogens and diseases caused differ from each other.
Hepatitis virus spreads in two main forms depending on the pathogen: hepatitis A and E through the alimentary canal (e.g. water and infected foods), hepatitis B, C, D and other blood viruses and organic fluids (sperm, vaginal discharge, saliva).
For travelers it is useful to get vaccinated against the virus A and B, against C there is no vaccine.
Hepatitis A symptoms appear two to three weeks after consuming infected foods, accompanied by general malaise, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After yellowish spots form on the skin and white of the eyes, the feces become light and the urine dark, healing takes place within two to three weeks.
One million people die every year worldwide from hepatitis B, the most serious variant of the disease, which causes liver tumors and liver cirrhosis.
The main reason is, according to estimates, that only one in ten people receive drug treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if it is not treated it can cause liver cirrhosis and liver tumors.
Most infected people do not know they have contracted the disease because pathogens subtly destroy liver cells, in many cases the first symptoms appear after 20-30 years.
So it is very important to prevent and carry out regular medical analysis.
This disease is much more frequent than average in three groups: those who had a blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts and tattooed.
Worldwide, the number of people infected with the chronic hepatitis C virus amounts to 200 million.
Since a routine laboratory examination also reveals the disease is worth turning to the family doctor when you notice any symptoms of unknown origin.
Recognized in time the disease is curable, the virus can be eliminated from the body, so the infectious power ceases and the formation of tumors can be prevented.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, first organized in 2004 worldwide by patient associations.
The aim is to draw attention to chronic viral hepatitis, the causes of its development and early recognition of the disease.
