What could be the best method to develop anti-collision technologies if not imitating the sensors of the obstacles found in nature?
For example, those of bees.
In the surprising project presented at CEATEC in Japan, hornets gave the initial strategic inspiration to Nissan engineers on how to build the next generation of anti-collision systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the biomimetic robot BR23C, a robotic mini car with bee properties, with the final aim of creating a system capable of scanning all collisions.
Flying bees form their own oval personal space that really looks very much like our protective shield - explained to the exhibition Kazuhiro Doi, director of the PR and R&D technologies sector.
Important is the role of the view of the bee, capable of a view of 300 degrees in every direction.
Engineers drew on the telemetric laser idea to copy the function of the bee's sight.
The BR23C detects obstacles up to two meters away within a 180-degree radius, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor that immediately turns it into a command to avoid collision.
In a fraction of a second the robot perceives the obstacle and then, imitating the movements of the bee, immediately changes direction turning the wheels of the necessary measure to avoid the accident.
This avoidance maneuver, in a different way from the current system, takes place in a completely instinctive way.
"If this were not the case, the robot car would not be able to react quickly to avoid collisions," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and the robot car project.
It must react instinctively and immediately because this technology corresponds to the damaged and innermost layer of the protective shield, within which the collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what a bee does to avoid the other bees.
This process must take place in the blink of an eye.
But unlike bees the deviation cannot go up or down or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional and in the direction of stezenability of the wheels.
In this way, instead of the infinite possibilities available to bees to avoid the other bees, the robot, as a possibility available, can rotate on itself, accelerate and slow down.
The BR23C is powered by lithium polymer batteries, lighter and higher energy density, which means that their lifespan is longer than lithium-ion ones.
According to Andoh, the instantaneity of the intelligent reaction is important, not data processing or even less the ability to store it.
This robot has to process some inputs in a few seconds and react.
There is no need to store them and react with intuitive logic based on previous maneuvering data, so it uses only a memory of a few dozen Kb.
There is no need for a gigabyte or megabyte memory.
This is the first step towards the development of a technology for the immediate avoidance of collisions that, foreseen at Nissan, within 10 years it can be installed on standard vehicles.
Further application possibilities may be unification with the GPS satellite navigation system which, avoiding obstacles on the road, leads to its destination.
