The fox in the chicken coop
In America, insurers on life and health, based on people’s medicinal purchasing data, often refuse to enter into an insurance contract.
Privacy experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
“There is a privacy program that the use of drug prescription data depends in any case on the approval of the data subject.
This program must be in independent hands, otherwise it is like entrusting the chicken coop to the fox" - writes the Washington Post citing Richard Dick author of the program to follow the prescriptions of the medicines.
The insurance companies subordinate the insurance rate and the amount due in the event of claims to the health status of the possible customer and if they consider too high the risk do not take out insurance.
Some time ago the customer had to undergo a medical examination and the contract was stipulated only after the examination.
Dick 10 years ago invented a much cheaper process: according to the customer identification code you can easily get information from pharmacies about what medicines he has purchased in the last year and a half and from this the program shows what diseases he suffers and in what health conditions he is in.
If you regularly buy large amounts of cholesterol reducers this means that the level of fat in the blood is in practice incurably high and is classified in the higher risk category.
On the market there are various versions of the program, some also determine the risk multiplier, to the insurer so in addition to paper work does not remain much, even if there are small difficulties.
Among the cons there are that some medicines can be used for multiple purposes, e.g. some compounds are usable against migraines or hot flashes, but are also effective against depression.
The latter, from the insurance-commercial point of view, is worth as a risk factor, the first two not.
For the request and data processing, apart from companies were formed and these, before obtaining the necessary information from pharmacies, ask for the approval of the patient.
Now the authorities oblige them to do so even if so far they have not imposed fines for negligence.
Some companies recently also process the result of laboratory tests and connect them to the treatment data in order to provide a more precise image of the health status of patients.
More and more companies have access to data and in parallel the control of use will be increasingly difficult.
There is a separate privacy law, but its validity extends only to health services and insurance.
In front of Congress there is a bill that gives the supervisory competence authorities to companies specialized in service data.
Richard Dick admits that it is not enough: for this reason he has developed a program that links the transmission of data with the approval expressed by the person concerned.
Another question is that the person concerned cannot deny approval because otherwise the insurers do not stipulate the contract.
So then at the end the hens are entrusted to the clemency of the fox.
