The first of these phenomena is the re-actualization, the extraordinary relaunch, of the double state-sovereignty category in relation to a sort of renationalization of the economy.
The crisis, in fact, is a crisis of banking-financial institutions which have, yes, full links with foreign countries, but which, above all, see the budgets of people and families who live in a single country, in a single state, involved in a very large measure.
This immediately creates a political problem for those who govern it: that is how to respond to the difficulties and protests of those people and families who, among other things, are also an electorate.
In short, the crisis appears economically worldwide but politically it is almost exclusively national.
Political internationalism seems essentially out of the game or not having much to say: the clear proof is given by the European Union which is divided as usual between the different interests and between the different state strategies fails to decide on any common political line.
And so it is from the government of every single State that everyone expects interventions, rescue and relaunch plans, new rules, and above all disbursement of funds: since when you get to the corners are only the States that own the economic resources, the mass of financial resources able to try to put things back on track.
And they also have the necessary means and the legitimacy to use them: two resources of immeasurable value, in certain circumstances, which probably no market and no international organization can ever dispose to a similar extent.
This new emphasis that the crisis places on the national-state-national element is in perfect harmony with the increasing importance that the most recent developments of the economy tend to attribute to a factor very closely linked to that element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, in fact, while we were convinced that we have now entered the realm of the network, of the increasingly sophisticated technology, of the immaterial, while we were convinced that globalized finance was now destined to dominate the world, we suddenly realized that our future will have to deal increasingly with those very unintangible things that are water, crops, oil.
All things that, look at a little, can certainly be transported from one place to another on the earth but are still absolutely linked to a limited space, to a territory.
So that those who find themselves sovereign, certainly have several more cards than those who are not, to those who have the misfortune to live in a place without crops, without oil and without water.
I come to the second novelty that portends a fracture.
Who says Territory, State, Government, inevitably says Politics, and therefore Leadership.
In this regard, the economic crisis seems to produce two convergent phenomena.
On the one hand, the awareness of the objective need for authoritative leadership, the request of someone who knows how to take matters into his own hands.
On the other hand, a wave of discredit for existing leadership, economic species, proved so inadequate and full of shadow areas.
And at the same time something even deeper and in a certain disturbing sense: a discredit, an impatience, an image of inadequacy, a sense of distance, which tends to involve the entire ruling class in an increasing number of countries in the West.
That is, it seems to make more and more course, in large sectors of the population, the conviction that before their actions are the same ideas of the social elites so far in vogue, their way of feeling and being, their culture in the overall sense of the term, to have made their own time and to be increasingly extraneous to the opinions of majorities.
The demand for leadership, in short, underground feeds a branched but powerful movement of delegitimization of the ruling classes and traditional political structures, which manifests itself in the sudden "electoral revolts" or in the sudden turns of the collective moods of the latter and very last times, from the conservative rise in Austria-Bavaria to the collapse of the Labour consensus in Britain, to the rebellion of the American congressmen.
One has the impression that the traditional elites, their parties, their programs, but also their rites, their newspapers, their accredited intellectuals, their formats would say someone, are increasingly struggling to understand, and therefore to represent, what is not taking shape in the deep strata of Western societies today and that the economic crisis invigorates, increases, is potentially unsuniing agitation.
Faced with all this, talking about a "rebellion of the masses" on the agenda would be frankly exaggerated.
But keeping your eyes open is not at all.
The superglue to walk on the walls
Defeat the laws of gravity with a super glue and in the future walk on walls like Spiderman.
It’s the goal of several American research centers and now a team from four institutes has come very close to us.
With a sticker of only 2.5 square centimeters, the researchers managed to keep a body of 100 kilograms on a vertical wall glued.
The American journal Science has published the findings of researchers from the University of Dayton, Akron, the Georgia Institute of Technology and the Air Force Research Laboratory.
The material invented by the team of scholars is an evolution of the existing ones that use a particular carbon structure, called carbon nanotubes.
“The principle of glue can be imagined as a series of tubes arranged like a pile of spaghetti,” explains Zhong Lin Wang of the Georgia Institute of Technology in Atlanta.
Scientists have been inspired by the legs of gechi, covered with microscopic hairs that are able to ensure perfect adherence to the animal.
Tests conducted on different materials, such as glass, Teflon and sandpaper, have shown that the new adhesive is ten times more powerful than the legs of these reptiles and at the same time "it easily detaches itself from the wall," explains Liming Dai, a researcher at the Faculty of Engineering at the University of Dayton.
WALKING ON MURI? -"This material could be useful as a transient sticker," adds Liming Dai.
Maybe to walk on the walls just like Spiderman? Perhaps yes, but researchers think of a much less fascinating use as the connection between electronic devices, because carbon nanotubes are conductors of heat and electric current.
Other applications could be about aerospace engineering.
For the moment, no superheroes.
