The image offered by the director Giuseppe Tornatore effectively photographs what is happening in the large Italian urban centers but also in the cities of the province.
The process of marginalization of cinemas, with the birth in the periphery of the great multiplexes and the consequent death by consummation of the monosals in the central areas of the cities, is one of those events that appear inevitable and incontrovertible to us but also has all the characteristics of a real cultural crime.
To disappear are often historical places and full of memory "it is as if a friend comes to pass away, an acquaintance with whom we have shared a piece of the street and many emotions", observes the director of Nuovo cinema Paradiso, the film that twenty years ago earned Tornatore the Oscar winner and the Grand Jury Prize of Cannes, and which told the poetry of a provincial room and nostalgia for a way of living the cinema lost perhaps forever.
The figures provided by Anec, the main association of exhibitors, are clear: in the last five years 316 traditional cinemas have closed their doors, and to pay the greatest price are mainly the halls in the main cities: 10 less in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closures, Emilia-Romagna excels with 82 single-room cinemas lost, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
