When energy comes from the waves now the big ones take to the field
It is an endless field, which occupies more than 70% of the planet’s surface and is now discovering it the world’s big energy companies.
Waves, currents, tides are the new renewable sources on which they have set their eyes, and now they try to get their hands on, giants like the Chevron.
The possibility of obtaining energy from the movements of the sea has been studied for a hundred years and in the 70s, in conjunction with the first oil crisis, the research intensified.
When the price of oil fell, around 1980, the idea of exploiting marine energy was put aside, but now environmentalist instances and the new increase in oil boosts the sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimated in 2007 that 15 percent of the world’s electricity needs could be covered by offshore seas operating facilities.
This amount would be twice as much as the nuclear power plant currently produced.
And in addition there would be the currents and the tides.
Colossi to the attack.
The first company to bet on marine energy was Enersis, which in 2005 signed an agreement to build a plant in the north of Portugal.
