Technology to be developed.
Experts speak of a technology still in its infancy, also because marine energy does not escape all doubts about the environmental impact.
For now, facilities such as the Portuguese or some in Scotland are small and do not seem to create major problems for the ecosystem.
However, technologies with a greater environmental impact must be used to produce large-scale energy.
And the choices are different: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of buoys connected to each other.
The thrust of the waves, which moves the buoys up and down is converted to hydraulic pressure by pistons and cylinders inside the floats.
The pressure spins a turbine which in turn feeds a generator.
Electricity is sent ashore through submarine cables.
For now there are four plants of this type being designed, waiting only for federal approval and part of the energy could be used for a military installation.
Verdant Power already produces power for a shopping mall and parking using six underwater turbines in the East River in New York.
The movement of water when there are tides makes the turbine blades spin, creating a rotary movement that powers a generator.
Verdant said it has a long list of customers waiting for the necessary authorizations to take advantage of the energy.
After the waves, the tides.
A particular interest, they say at the Institute for the Research of Electricity, deserves the potential of the tides at this time.
Although it is an intermittent phenomenon, the tide is more predictable than wind, sun or waves and therefore more reliable as an energy source.
